[{'action': 'opened', 'author': 'natefinch', 'comment_id': None, 'datetime': '2017-08-07 19:27:14+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': "**Note: I would be willing to implement this if others think it is valuable**

In working with another generator, I needed a function that didn't exist in the funcMap, and adding it required a PR to the generator.  It occurred to me that it would be very easy to implement a plugin system to allow users to implement their own functions in the funcMap.

Here's my suggestion - plugins are very simple executables that follow this pattern:

If a plugin executable is run with no arguments, it should output to stdout a newline delimited list of function names.  Hugo would run all the plugins[1] at startup and keep a reference of which plugin produced which function name, for when they're called from a template.

When a template calls one of the plugin's functions, the plugin executable is run with with the function name as an argument, and any further arguments are sent as a json array to the plugin's stdin[2].  The result of the program should be json formatted and written to stdout.  If an error is encountered, the executable should exit with a non-zero exit code, and write any error text to stderr.

Bam, now any user can create a plugin in any language they want to extend the functionality of Hugo to support any function they want.

[1] How plugins are discovered by Hugo is left to the developer.  I don't really care if it's a magic directory or specially named executables in the $PATH or whatever.

[2]  We do this to avoid OS character limits on executable arguments.", 'title': 'Feature Suggestion: Support plugins for extending funcMap', 'type': 'issue'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'digitalcraftsman', 'comment_id': 320760745.0, 'datetime': '2017-08-07 19:43:23+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': "It would be a very powerful feature for users to be able to extend the funcMap with custom functions. 

But from the POV of a theme maintainer I would be facing the following problems:

**Plugin distribution:** Most themes are publicly accessible as a Git repository which users should only have to clone in order to use it. As themes should work out of the box it would be necessary to track executables in a CVS as well unless there is some dead simple package manager.

Furthermore, executables are mostly platform dependent. Writing a plugin in Go isn't hard but I would have to provide executables for all major platforms (incl. 32 and 64 bit versions). This would create even more bloat.

**Versioning:** Plugins can change over the time, e.g. through the addition of new features or bug fixes. Sometimes a piece of software can change it's behavior which might cause errors. This makes it harder to detect errors because you can say plugin xx with version 1.xxx is not compatible with the current state of the theme.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'natefinch', 'comment_id': 320773769.0, 'datetime': '2017-08-07 20:37:35+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': "This is a very interesting point.  I hadn't thought of this from the vantage of requiring a plugin for a theme, but that does make sense.  I'd just been thinking about hacking up an existing theme and needing different functions for it. 

Of course, if it's a script (python or otherwise) it could be included with the theme, but that does then require that the host have python installed, which is a problem for Windows users.

I wonder if something like embedded lua would be a way to avoid that - https://github.com/yuin/gopher-lua  of course, then you have to write the functions in lua :/", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'bep', 'comment_id': 320780390.0, 'datetime': '2017-08-07 21:05:22+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': 'Doing template func plugins via `os/exec` sounds tempting and simple, but there are lots of issues floating to surface once you start thinking about it (performance, security, distribution, support). I have always thought about potential plugins in Hugo on a more granular level; piping a template string into a python trim func  does not sound very fast for 10K pages.

Embedded Lua does sound interesting and is the way a big project like Wikipedia has gone with their end-user provided scripts.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'digitalcraftsman', 'comment_id': 320782685.0, 'datetime': '2017-08-07 21:14:59+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': "Using an embedded language might be the sweet spot. Distributing executables is a hassle due to the vast amount of platforms and unflexible. Interpreted languages like Python would require a runtime environment.

Embedded languages also might be easier to use than RPC-based plugins (see #1239).

While glancing over the README of the gopher-lua repo I saw the `DoFile` method to load scripts. It would be neat to have scripts as simple text files in a special directory which is watched by Hugo. This way functions could be added, removed and updated ad hoc. Simple text files 

However, I don't know how goper-lua will perform / slow down Hugo, nor how much the Hugo executable would grow. @username_2 also mentioned other aspects that have to be considered as well.

While this is just wishful thinking and definitely needs a more precise specification it could go beyond template functions.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'natefinch', 'comment_id': 333730404.0, 'datetime': '2017-10-03 03:43:10+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': "FYI, we just built a plugin system like this for Gnorm: https://gnorm.org/templates/plugins/

It's basic now, just running an executable in a specified directory.  But I intend to enhance it so it can understand how to run common languages like .py .rb .go etc... yes it'll require that you have that language on your machine, but it's a lot easier to implement this than embedding a whole new language in your binary, *and* requiring people to write plugins in that language.

Not that I wouldn't also like lua in Gnorm, it's more work.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'natefinch', 'comment_id': 334243773.0, 'datetime': '2017-10-04 18:14:48+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': 'Hmm... skylark might be better (python is more popular than lua).  Could be distributed as plaintext with a theme.

https://github.com/google/skylark
https://godoc.org/github.com/google/skylark#ExecFile', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}

<issue_start><issue_comment>Title: Feature Suggestion: Support plugins for extending funcMap
username_0: **Note: I would be willing to implement this if others think it is valuable**

In working with another generator, I needed a function that didn't exist in the funcMap, and adding it required a PR to the generator.  It occurred to me that it would be very easy to implement a plugin system to allow users to implement their own functions in the funcMap.

Here's my suggestion - plugins are very simple executables that follow this pattern:

If a plugin executable is run with no arguments, it should output to stdout a newline delimited list of function names.  Hugo would run all the plugins[1] at startup and keep a reference of which plugin produced which function name, for when they're called from a template.

When a template calls one of the plugin's functions, the plugin executable is run with with the function name as an argument, and any further arguments are sent as a json array to the plugin's stdin[2].  The result of the program should be json formatted and written to stdout.  If an error is encountered, the executable should exit with a non-zero exit code, and write any error text to stderr.

Bam, now any user can create a plugin in any language they want to extend the functionality of Hugo to support any function they want.

[1] How plugins are discovered by Hugo is left to the developer.  I don't really care if it's a magic directory or specially named executables in the $PATH or whatever.

[2]  We do this to avoid OS character limits on executable arguments.
<issue_comment>username_1: It would be a very powerful feature for users to be able to extend the funcMap with custom functions. 

But from the POV of a theme maintainer I would be facing the following problems:

**Plugin distribution:** Most themes are publicly accessible as a Git repository which users should only have to clone in order to use it. As themes should work out of the box it would be necessary to track executables in a CVS as well unless there is some dead simple package manager.

Furthermore, executables are mostly platform dependent. Writing a plugin in Go isn't hard but I would have to provide executables for all major platforms (incl. 32 and 64 bit versions). This would create even more bloat.

**Versioning:** Plugins can change over the time, e.g. through the addition of new features or bug fixes. Sometimes a piece of software can change it's behavior which might cause errors. This makes it harder to detect errors because you can say plugin xx with version 1.xxx is not compatible with the current state of the theme.
<issue_comment>username_0: This is a very interesting point.  I hadn't thought of this from the vantage of requiring a plugin for a theme, but that does make sense.  I'd just been thinking about hacking up an existing theme and needing different functions for it. 

Of course, if it's a script (python or otherwise) it could be included with the theme, but that does then require that the host have python installed, which is a problem for Windows users.

I wonder if something like embedded lua would be a way to avoid that - https://github.com/yuin/gopher-lua  of course, then you have to write the functions in lua :/
<issue_comment>username_2: Doing template func plugins via `os/exec` sounds tempting and simple, but there are lots of issues floating to surface once you start thinking about it (performance, security, distribution, support). I have always thought about potential plugins in Hugo on a more granular level; piping a template string into a python trim func  does not sound very fast for 10K pages.

Embedded Lua does sound interesting and is the way a big project like Wikipedia has gone with their end-user provided scripts.
<issue_comment>username_1: Using an embedded language might be the sweet spot. Distributing executables is a hassle due to the vast amount of platforms and unflexible. Interpreted languages like Python would require a runtime environment.

Embedded languages also might be easier to use than RPC-based plugins (see #1239).

While glancing over the README of the gopher-lua repo I saw the `DoFile` method to load scripts. It would be neat to have scripts as simple text files in a special directory which is watched by Hugo. This way functions could be added, removed and updated ad hoc. Simple text files 

However, I don't know how goper-lua will perform / slow down Hugo, nor how much the Hugo executable would grow. @username_2 also mentioned other aspects that have to be considered as well.

While this is just wishful thinking and definitely needs a more precise specification it could go beyond template functions.
<issue_comment>username_0: FYI, we just built a plugin system like this for Gnorm: https://gnorm.org/templates/plugins/

It's basic now, just running an executable in a specified directory.  But I intend to enhance it so it can understand how to run common languages like .py .rb .go etc... yes it'll require that you have that language on your machine, but it's a lot easier to implement this than embedding a whole new language in your binary, *and* requiring people to write plugins in that language.

Not that I wouldn't also like lua in Gnorm, it's more work.
<issue_comment>username_0: Hmm... skylark might be better (python is more popular than lua).  Could be distributed as plaintext with a theme.

https://github.com/google/skylark
https://godoc.org/github.com/google/skylark#ExecFile
<issue_comment>username_3: this issue should be reopened, i need a way to format date to jalali, embeded script seems a very good solution.
<issue_comment>username_0: POC here: #5521
<issue_comment>username_4: @username_3, create a separate issue for your calendar/date issue.

[{'action': 'opened', 'author': 'norfindel', 'comment_id': None, 'datetime': '2019-04-09 22:38:51+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': "But actually, if you do that, apt will download roughly 5GB of files and install stuff that has nothing to do with kicad, like “Claws Mail”. They were more than 3000 packages, IIRC.

It also installs what seems to be every electronics application known to man.

So, probably it would be a good idea to NOT suggest to do that, and just install kicad, kicad-library and kicad-doc packages? (or whatever is considered a full installation, it's the first time that i attempt to install kicad)

Regards", 'title': 'apt install --install-suggests kicad a very bad idea', 'type': 'issue'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'nickoe', 'comment_id': 481469768.0, 'datetime': '2019-04-09 22:54:34+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': 'What was the exact output that it proposed? I tried this earlier today and only got new kicad stuff. Maybe you mistyped something?', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}

Please do replace "sudo apt install --install-suggests kicad" at [http://kicad-pcb.org/download/ubuntu/](http://kicad-pcb.org/download/ubuntu/).

![kicad install on lubuntu](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/35882530/65846284-69ae6f00-e37c-11e9-9af9-f1fa43707ff0.png)

Steps to replicate:
1. Install or try [Lubuntu 18.04 LTS](http://cdimage.ubuntu.com/lubuntu/releases/18.04/release/lubuntu-18.04.3-desktop-amd64.iso).
2. sudo apt-get update
3. sudo apt-get upgrade
4. sudo add-apt-repository --yes ppa:js-reynaud/kicad-5.1
5. sudo apt update
6. sudo apt install --install-suggests kicad', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}

<issue_start><issue_comment>Title: apt install --install-suggests kicad a very bad idea
username_0: But actually, if you do that, apt will download roughly 5GB of files and install stuff that has nothing to do with kicad, like “Claws Mail”. They were more than 3000 packages, IIRC.

It also installs what seems to be every electronics application known to man.

So, probably it would be a good idea to NOT suggest to do that, and just install kicad, kicad-library and kicad-doc packages? (or whatever is considered a full installation, it's the first time that i attempt to install kicad)

Regards
<issue_comment>username_1: What was the exact output that it proposed? I tried this earlier today and only got new kicad stuff. Maybe you mistyped something?

<issue_start><issue_comment>Title: 'hugo clean'
username_0: - [I've noticed—as I move things around, change names, and bring things in and out of the static folder—that Hugo doesn't clear the public folder of this "old stuff."
  I've resorted to deleting it, on occasion, just to "start anew."—](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/hugo-discuss/G6LkdLX3frQ)@dkebler
- [If I render my site, then change the name of a content file and re-render, the old rendered HTML files stay in the output directory. This easily can cause me to have some duplicate-, or just plain "old" data in the output directory.—](https://github.com/spf13/hugo/issues/379#issue-39321107)@natefinch
- [I forgot to clear out the public directory; I'm not entirely satisfied with its nomenclature either. However, these are largely self-inflicted pains.
  I'm not satisfied with nuking the directory via the command line approach.
  I also think that this is something Hugo should be responsible for, as it is the one putting the files in its own directories—it should be capable of managing those resources better: or, at a minimum, clean up after itself.
  I'm for having some solution to cleaning up the public folder, even if it's just a delete process.—](https://discuss.gohugo.io/t/hugo-t-theme-behavior/221/3)@mohae
- [Files that were created in the wrong directory or with the wrong title will remain. If you leave them, you might get confused by them later.](https://github.com/spf13/hugo/blame/6eff9e501534dfa952b059f446faf9eff097aef7/docs/content/tutorials/creating-a-new-theme.md#L402) [and]
  [Purge the `public/` directory (optional, but useful if you want to start with a clean slate).—](https://github.com/spf13/hugo/blame/6eff9e501534dfa952b059f446faf9eff097aef7/docs/content/tutorials/creating-a-new-theme.md#L415)@mdhender
- [Maybe: something like a `.hugoignore` file, to white-list files you want to keep.—](https://github.com/spf13/hugo/issues/379#issuecomment-50959166)@natefinch
- [Simpler just to let the user define one or more commands to run. For me, `rm -rf *` would work fine.—](https://github.com/spf13/hugo/issues/379#issuecomment-52717542)@natefinch
- [I'm fine with adding an extra `clean` step to my deploy script.—](https://discuss.gohugo.io/t/hugo-t-theme-behavior/221/2)@bep
- [Behavior 1): Static change -> sync static files
  Behavior 2): Other file changes (template, content, etc) -> render of complete site.
  I think behavior 2) could improve to: first do a complete filesync (including deleting all non static files), then do the re-render.
  This would have the advantage of not copying over all the images, etc., that are in the static directory, while providing a clean directory for the rendering to happen in.—](https://github.com/spf13/hugo/issues/379#issuecomment-59817813)@spf13
- [Hugo's big selling point is speed. If this "complete filesync" makes the live-reload less snappy, I'm less happy.—](https://github.com/spf13/hugo/issues/379#issuecomment-59820271)@bep
- [I don't want to implement/review "delete folders" code in an open-source project. There are plenty of effective ways to handle this:
  1. Do a `rm -rf [public/]` in a shell script;
  2. Separate development and production build targets.—](https://github.com/spf13/hugo/issues/379#issuecomment-146985672)@bep

In summary:
1. Some web site creators (and maintainers) seem uncomfortable with the command line (in general);
2. Some Hugo tutorials recommend purging the `./public/` directory by means of the command line, in order to aid development;
3. Purging manually involves the (arguably) somewhat scary command: `rm -rf public`;
4. Some Hugo users are reluctant to use `rm -rf {argument}`;
5. For Hugo old hands, this reluctance is no problem, but for newish Hugo users, it does IMO seem to be an issue;
6. A subcommand `clean` is familiar (at least to some people), thus easily explainable: see (for instance) `make clean`;
7. Currently Hugo is unlike most other programs in how its users do the necessary cleanup.

To help Hugo (by slightly aiding its evangelism), the sweet spot IMO would be these goals:
1. Help those web site creators relatively uncomfortable with the command line;
2. Provide a Hugo command to `clean` the configured output directory (this isn't always `./public/`);
3. Keep a `clean` command separate. (Don't complicate the `hugo` rendering process);
4. Add only a tiny amount of code.

Based on all this, Hugo should provide IMO a command `hugo clean`.

For some users, `hugo clean` would "feel" IMO safer than `rm -rf {argument}`, for two reasons:
1. It would be an official Hugo command;
2. It would avoid some users' uncomfortable feeling (observable above) regarding possibly deleting the wrong files through their use of the "powerful and dangerous" command `rm -rf {argument}`.

Later, IMO Hugo could provide an option `--keep-static` to speed cleaning (and rendering) when users know their static files haven't changed. This option might apply to `hugo clean` and `hugo`.

tl;dr

Hugo's evangelistic interest would be served by helping some users with their command line `rm -rf {argument}` discomfort, if this help is merely a tiny addition to the Hugo codebase, by means of adding IMO a `hugo clean` command.
<issue_comment>username_1: @acnebs The point is, as I understand it, that the writing of the `rm -rf` command itself is handled by the user, rather than Hugo. This means that if the command breaks, for whatever reason, and deletes more than it should, it's obviously 100% the fault of the user, and not a bug in Hugo which is deleting peoples sites, or worse yet, their entire disk. There are plenty of valid codepaths which would look completely fine, pass code review, be shipped, and then result in someone nuking their entire OS.

There are problems deploying this on shared server environments or any method that does not allow shell+compile access.

There are a couple of solutions I am toying with.

ONE:
Create a Micro-Appliance.
This can be done by setting up a beaglebone with access via dynamic domain name to act as a PhantomJS bridge.  This allows you to deploy these yourself to friends and family etc.
Beaglebones are between $35 and $65 depending on which flavor you get.  With case and power supply add another $15 per unit.  This is a one time charge if you have people volunteering bandwidth and power.

TWO:
Create a Cloud Deploy Image.
This can also be done via dynamic cloud spinups (such as on Amazon AWS).
This is easier but more costly over time.

Automated proxy list maintenance can be included on these also, to move this coding/overhead into the appliance, preventing the need to set up CRON for this task with this rss-bridge app.

<issue_start><issue_comment>Title: Need to get RESULTANT (Rendered) HTML from dynamic pages...
username_0: Hi,

Some very important problems can be solved by gaining access to the RESULTANT (Rendered) HTML.
This means that the page is loaded, and javascript is executed, THEN the HTML result is returned.

There is a way to do this.
It is based around creating a PhantomJS (http://phantomjs.org/) bridge.

There are problems deploying this on shared server environments or any method that does not allow shell+compile access.

There are a couple of solutions I am toying with.

ONE:
Create a Micro-Appliance.
This can be done by setting up a beaglebone with access via dynamic domain name to act as a PhantomJS bridge.  This allows you to deploy these yourself to friends and family etc.
Beaglebones are between $35 and $65 depending on which flavor you get.  With case and power supply add another $15 per unit.  This is a one time charge if you have people volunteering bandwidth and power.

TWO:
Create a Cloud Deploy Image.
This can also be done via dynamic cloud spinups (such as on Amazon AWS).
This is easier but more costly over time.

Automated proxy list maintenance can be included on these also, to move this coding/overhead into the appliance, preventing the need to set up CRON for this task with this rss-bridge app.

Questions/Comments: get at me.
username_0<issue_closed>
<issue_comment>username_2: I'm really interested into developing some phantomjs integration, because more and more websites now require javascript, like Thingiverse since last update 😒
